data.content:
Yes! In MSTest 3.7+, use **ValueTuples** instead of `object[]` for type-safe `DynamicData`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- Return type: `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`
- Data rows: `["value", true]` → `("value", true)`

This gives you compile-time type checking — if you accidentally swap a `string` and `bool`, the compiler catches it instead of a runtime `InvalidCastException`. The test method signature stays the same.

If you also need display names per case, wrap with `TestDataRow<T>`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<TestDataRow<(string input, bool expected)>> TestData =>
[
    new(("valid@email.com", true)) { DisplayName = "Valid email" },
    new(("invalid", false))        { DisplayName = "Missing domain" },
    new(("", false))               { DisplayName = "Empty string" },
];
```
